1920√ó1080, 270.3 KB
The Korean who fought in the Japanese, Soviet and German armies!

The name of this unique man is Yang Kyoungjong. He was born in 1920 in the city of Sinuiju, which, like the rest of Korea, was part of the Japanese Empire back then.

At the age of 18, Kyoungjong was mobilized to the Kwantung Army, which, in the Spring-Summer of 1939, fought against the Soviet troops at the Khalkhin-Gol River. There, he was taken prisoner.

According to British historian Anthony Beevor, in 1942, a difficult year for the Soviet Union, the Korean, along with thousands of other prisoners, were mobilized into the Red Army.

In early 1943, near Kharkov, Kyoungjong again found himself in captivity - this time by the Germans. There, Jan admitted about his service in the Japanese forces and offered to join one of the Eastern Legions for collaborators among Soviet prisoners of war.

The third time Yang Kyoungjong was captured was in June 1944, after the landing of Allied troops in Normandy - he was captured by paratroopers of the 101st Airborne Division of the United States.

The Korean spent some time in a prisoner-of-war camp in Great Britain and, soon after the end of the war, moved to the United States, where he lived until his death in 1992.

Many researchers regard Yang Kyoungjong's incredible story with a great deal of doubt. In Korea, however, it is considered to be true. In 2011, a feature movie based on his biography, ‚ÄòMy Way‚Äô, was filmed there.

Meanwhile, hundreds of Koreans really fought in the Red Army during the war. One of them, Captain Alexander Min, who fell in battle in 1944, was posthumously awarded the title of ‚ÄòHero of the Soviet Union‚Äô for exemplary performance in combat missions and courage.

How the horrific story of Soviet Union‚Äôs ‚Äòcannibal island‚Äô unfolded

"All over the island you could see human meat being torn, cut up and hung on trees. The glades were littered with corpses," was how a resident of the Siberian village of Nazino described the terrible tragedy she witnessed in 1933.

Then, in May, more than 6,000 people ‚Äì speculators, vagrants, beggars, prostitutes and other "socially harmful and declasse elements" ‚Äì were shipped on barges to an uninhabited island on the Ob River near the village.

The repressed were on their way to special labor settlements in the east to work for the good of the state. However, these settlements were not ready for such an influx of people.

As a result, the group of people got stranded on the island, where they suffered from cold, hunger and cruelty at the hands of the guards. Tiny food rations were in short supply, leading to widespread cannibalism. People were grabbed, killed and completely eaten.

Another resident of Nazino recalled how a woman from "Death-Island" was brought to their village and had all the flesh on her calves cut off: "Her feet were freezing, and the woman wrapped them in rags. She moved on her own. She looked like an old woman, but in reality she was in her early 40s."

It was not until a month later that the sick, exhausted people were evacuated from the island. However, they continued to die in the unprepared barracks of the special settlements. All in all, during the journey, a little more than 2,000 survived.

A special commission found 31 mass graves on the island with 50-70 corpses in each. More than 80 special settlers and escorts were brought to trial, 23 of them were shot for "looting and beating", 11 people ‚Äì for cannibalism.

The general public learned about the "cannibal island" from declassified state archives only in the late 1980s on the eve of the collapse of the Soviet Union.
